{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"alias":"large-sleepful-needlefish","description":"## Why\nThe plan-v2 impact model auto-scores four failure modes at >=0.85 (the hard floor), above every blocking threshold. One of them, `ac_unverifiable`, currently conflates two defects of very different severity: a criterion with NO oracle at all (genuinely untestable - deserves the auto-block) and a criterion with a real but UNDER-SPECIFIED oracle (a check exists but the exact command/file/expected value is not spelled out - a refinement, not a plan-killer). Block-round data (epic d195 dogfooding: 10-11 rounds of valid-but-terminal-detail blocks) shows the second grade dominating block loops. Splitting the axis removes the largest source of high-severity blocks that do not threaten plan quality, while keeping the true missing-oracle floor intact.\n\n## What\nGrade the `ac_unverifiable` severity attribute into two values in the plan-review verification model and impact function: `missing_oracle` keeps the 0.85 hard floor; `underspecified_oracle` scores below the blocking tier (advisory-range impact) so it surfaces and is coached but does not auto-block. Update the verify-pass rubric prompt so the verifier assigns the grade explicitly, and thread the grade losslessly into the sidecar for future calibration.\n\n## Scope\n- src/rebar/llm/review_kernel/decide.py (or plan-review impact fn site): floor logic keyed on the new grade.\n- The plan-review verification output schema + verify rubric prompt: the graded field, with definitions and one example of each grade.\n- Sidecar slimming: persist the grade.\n- Unit tests pinning both grades' impact scores and schema round-trip; fixture labels if the labeled set gains graded rows.\n- DESIGN INPUT (hard prerequisite): the calibration-3 replay evidence recorded on this story by the dependency ticket - thresholds and floor values chosen here must cite it.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] The verification model distinguishes missing_oracle from underspecified_oracle for ac_unverifiable, with schema validation accepting exactly the closed grade set and the rubric prompt defining both grades with an example each.\n- [ ] Impact scoring: missing_oracle retains the hard floor (>=0.85); underspecified_oracle scores below the lowest blocking threshold in force after calibration 3, pinned by unit tests for both grades.\n- [ ] The grade is persisted in the REVIEW_RESULT sidecar for every ac_unverifiable finding (lossless for future calibration replays), pinned by a test.\n- [ ] The chosen floor/score values cite the calibration-3 evidence comment recorded on this story.","id":"7d91-55fc-e07c-4101","parent_id":"","priority":2,"tags":[],"ticket_type":"story","title":"Split ac_unverifiable hard-floor axis: missing_oracle vs underspecified_oracle (plan-v2)"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1784139183216908001,"uuid":"4a3c7cd6-58c0-4bad-b9a0-4c1c98ea6956"}